              "TTFT measures how smoothly tokens continue arriving, while TPOT measures total GPU utilization.",
              "TTFT measures responsiveness before output starts, while TPOT measures the fluidity of token generation once output is streaming.",
              "TTFT measures model accuracy, while TPOT measures memory fragmentation.",
              "TTFT measures network latency only, while TPOT measures preprocessing latency only."
            ],
            "answer": "The correct answer is B. Time to First Token captures how quickly the system begins responding, while Time Per Output Token determines how smooth the ongoing generation feels. The other answers confuse latency metrics with utilization, correctness, or unrelated subsystem delays.",
            "learning_objective": "Differentiate TTFT and TPOT as distinct dimensions of LLM serving performance."
          },
          {
            "question_type": "MCQ",
            "question": "Why is the decode phase of LLM serving typically memory-bandwidth-bound rather than compute-bound?",
            "choices": [
              "Because each generated token requires rereading large model weights from memory, so moving bytes dominates arithmetic work.",
              "Because LLMs perform no matrix operations during decode.",
              "Because decode disables batching, forcing the GPU to use only one core.",
              "Because postprocessing always dominates token generation time."
            ],
            "answer": "The correct answer is A. The chapter's token-generation model emphasizes that each output token pays a memory-movement cost to bring weights back into active computation, making bandwidth the dominant limiter. LLMs still perform matrix math, and batching plus postprocessing do not erase the underlying memory-wall constraint.",
            "learning_objective": "Explain why LLM decode latency is governed by memory bandwidth."
          },
          {
            "question_type": "SHORT",
            "question": "Beam search often improves output quality relative to greedy decoding, but why can it be a problematic default for latency-sensitive production serving?",
            "answer": "Beam search keeps multiple candidate sequences alive, so its compute and memory costs scale roughly with beam width instead of staying close to one path. The operational consequence is higher latency and lower throughput, which can be unacceptable when the product values responsiveness over marginal quality gains.",
            "learning_objective": "Evaluate decoding-strategy trade-offs for production LLM serving."
          },
          {
            "question_type": "MCQ",
            "question": "What problem does prefix caching solve most directly?",
            "choices": [
              "It compresses model weights so they fit into smaller container images.",
              "It reuses precomputed KV states for common prompt prefixes, reducing redundant prefill work across related requests.",
              "It guarantees that all generations have the same sequence length, simplifying batching.",
              "It eliminates the need for tokenization on the client."
            ],
            "answer": "The correct answer is B. Prefix caching avoids recomputing shared context such as system prompts or repeated RAG prefixes, reducing both prefill compute and memory traffic. It does not make all outputs equal length, nor does it replace tokenization or weight compression.",
            "learning_objective": "Explain how prefix caching improves LLM serving efficiency."
          },
          {
            "question_type": "SHORT",
            "question": "Explain the trade-off involved in KV-cache offloading from GPU memory to host RAM or NVMe.",
            "answer": "Offloading prevents out-of-memory failures and allows longer contexts or more tenants than VRAM alone can hold. The cost is a retrieval latency tax over slower interconnects, so it improves capacity and robustness at the expense of per-request responsiveness when offloaded state must be brought back.",
            "learning_objective": "Analyze the capacity-versus-latency trade-off in KV-cache offloading."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
